Verify Square Footage of a Property in Maryland

Often, Realtors will add the basement square footage to a listing to make their property more appealing to buyers. Although this is not deceitful, it can make it difficult for a buyer to compare properties that do not have the basement square footage added to the listing. Always have your Realtor verify the square footage of the home. In most cases, the listed square footage does not include the basement square footage regardless of it being finished or unfinished.

In this example, only one property has included the basement square footage so my Comparative Market Analysis was thrown off. After checking SDAT, for above grade square footage, I can verify the square footage not including the basement. Now I’m comparing apples to apples. 

Let me know if you need some assistance with this example. I’d love to assist you!

Many people in the real estate industry might not appreciate this post.

A friend from my junior high school reached out, seeking assistance in selling her cousin’s home. Upon meeting her cousin, I discovered that she aimed to pay off her property, as investors had informed her that the house was valued at only $140,000. Given its subpar condition and insufficient space for the family, a quick sale was necessary. In usual cases like this, an agent might buy it for $140,000 or pass it to a developer acquaintance, expecting to relist it after renovations. However, I don’t operate that way. 

Historically, we as Black individuals have sometimes exploited each other for profit. From times of slavery to selling drugs and influencing the community negatively through rap music, we’ve seen patterns of self-destructive behavior. Even now, what’s called wholesaling can involve taking property from those who’ve managed to retain it, a practice I can’t endorse.
I refused to strip my clients of what might be their final chance for a substantial profit. So, I assured my client that her house was worth far more than $140,000. I assured her, “I’ve got you—just trust me and the process.” Ultimately, I managed to sell her home for $280,000, double her initial estimate. She left with over $100,000, a rewarding outcome for her years as a homeowner. Her words, “you were God sent,” held more value for me than the potential earnings from exploiting her misconceptions.

If you’re navigating a situation involving representing your family’s home sale, let me help. Contact me to safeguard your family’s investment—I’ll ensure you receive every dollar you’re entitled to.

Please share this with friends and family members that may need my assistance. But in the meantime, Stay Woke!

What kind of education is this?

This is what new construction builders don’t want you to know! 🙅🏾‍♂️

When you purchase a new home, you’re responsible for 100% of the transfer and recordation charges.

When you buy a preowned home, it’s typical to split those charges 50/50.

So what does that look like on paper? 🤷🏾‍♂️

For example, transfer and recordation charges on a $700,000 home in PG County will be $17,500 inclusive of state transfer tax, county transfer tax and county recordation tax.

If you purchase a new construction home, you have to pay that $17,500 so that $20,000 credit that the builder is giving you is spent on these fees with $2,500 to spare.

If you purchase a preowned home, you would be responsible for $8,750. That’s a difference of almost $9,000,

Take this into consideration when choosing your new home. I’m always here to help!

If you have any questions, please feel free to reach out to me!

NEW CONSTRUCTION VS PRELOVED HOME: WHICH ONE?

New Construction:

Pros:

Modern Amenities: Enjoy the latest features and technology.
Customization: Often allows for personalized design choices.

Energy Efficiency: New homes often have better insulation and energy-efficient systems.

Cons:

Cost: Initial purchase price and customization can be pricier.
Landscaping: May lack mature trees and established landscaping.

Unestablished Neighborhood: Limited amenities and community history.

Preloved Homes:

Pros:

Character and Charm: Unique architectural details and established aesthetics.

Mature Landscaping: Enjoy well-developed gardens and trees.

Established Neighborhood: Access to community amenities and a sense of history.

Cons:

Maintenance: May require more immediate repairs or renovations.

Outdated Features: Older homes may have outdated systems or layouts.

Less Energy Efficiency: Older homes might be less energy-efficient.

Consider your preferences and priorities to find the perfect fit!
